Recommended for the crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root initiation: 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage: 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage: 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage: 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

Recommended for the crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root initiation: 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage: 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage: 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage: 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

The crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root intiation : 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage : 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage : 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage : 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

Recommended  for The crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root intiation : 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage : 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage : 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage : 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

III- Active tillering stage : 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage : 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage : 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.

Method for Preperation of bordex pest 
1. Dissolve one kilogram of copper sulphate in 5 liter of water in plastic bucket.
2. Dissolve one kilogram of quick lime in 5 liter of water seperately in plastic bucket.
3. Both solution are mixed in one bucket same time.
4. If the prepare mixture is in acidic range, it can be brought to neutral or near alkaline condition by adding some more lime solution into the mixture. 
5. To test the neutrality of the mixture, dip a well polished knife or a sickle in the mixture for few minutes. If reddish deposit appears on the knife/sickle, it indicates the acidic nature of the mixture.

KCCAns:
Pusa Hybrid-5

The good growth of the plant and the branches are raised above, the fruits are of medium length, bright and dark purple color. Sowing takes 85-90 days in first truncation. Suitable for Karnataka, Kerala, Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, except the plains and beaches of northern and central India. The yield is 450 to 650 quintals per hectare.

Pusa Hybrid-6

Plants are moderately straight. Fruits are round, shiny, attractive, purple, each fruit weighs around 200 grams. Sowing takes 85-90 days in first discharge. The yield is 400-600 quintals per hectare.

Pusa Hybrid 9

Plants are standing straight The fruits are elliptic, round, bright purple. Each fruit weighs around 300 grams. It takes 85-90 days to first sowing of sowing. Suitable for Gujarat and Maharashtra region. Its average yield is 500 quintals per hectare.

Pusa Revolution

The fruits of this type are of medium purple in dark purple color. This type has been found suitable for both season and winter season. Its average yield is 300 quintals per hectare.

Pusa Bhairav

Its fruits are somewhat thick and violet in dark purple color. This type of fruit-melting disease is resistant.

Pusa Purple Cluster

Plants are standing straight. Leaves are mousetrap. Fruits range between 9 to 12 cm long and in flakes. This type is suitable for hill areas. This type of fruit and stem piercer, is resistant to bacterial and vomiting disease.
Pusa untimely plants are medium and straight. Fruits are thin, violet color. The fruits seem to be in the flakes. This type of type is cold disease resistant.

Pusa point

This type of eggplant is small, round and shiny. The color of which is dark purple stalks. This type is ready in 90 days. The average yield is 300 quintals per hectare. This type is suitable for the Northern Plains.

Pusa Best 31

Its fruits are elliptic, round, bright, dark purple and medium-sized. Sowing takes 85-90 days in first truncation. The average yield is 425 quintals per hectare. This type is suitable for northern plains and western areas.

Puscha good luck

Its fruits are round, bright, dark purple and medium-sized. The average weight of the fruit is 200 grams. The first Tudai crop can be done 85 days after planting. This type is suitable for the Northern Plains. Its average yield is 400 quintals per hectare.

Pusa sprout

This is an advanced type which is worth breaking in 75 days from the date of sowing. Fruits are small, dark purple, elliptical rounds are bright. Its average yield is 350 quintals per hectare.

Method for Preperation of bordex pest 
1. Dissolve one kilogram of copper sulphate in 5 liter of water in plastic bucket.
2. Dissolve one kilogram of quick lime in 5 liter of water seperately in plastic bucket.
3. Both solution are mixed in one bucket same time.
4. If the prepare mixture is in acidic range, it can be brought to neutral or near alkaline condition by adding some more lime solution into the mixture. 
5. To test the neutrality of the mixture, dip a well polished knife or a sickle in the mixture for few minutes. If reddish deposit appears on the knife/sickle, it indicates the acidic nature of the mixture.

KCCAns:
1- Visit the field in which sampling is to be done by jig-jig and mark it at 10-15 places so that all parts of the farm can be included in it.

2- Remove debris, debris etc. from the upper surface on the selected places.

3- 15 cm at all these places (6-9 inch) dig deeper V shaped cord. Cleansing the pot from the top of the scalp, up to 2 cm from the top. Remove the thick soil from the bottom and put it in a clean bucket or tray.

4- Mix the collected clay well with hand and make a round pile by putting it on clean clothes. Remove the clay from finger to four equal parts and remove the soil separately. Now mix the remaining two parts again and make the rounds. Repeat this procedure until almost half of the remains are left in the soil. This representative will be sample.

5- Keep the dry soil sample in a clean plastic bag and put it in a garment bag. Insert a notice sheet with a sample on which all the information is written, inside a plastic bag and outside a garment bag.

6- Now send these prepared samples to the soil testing laboratory.
